Fix stack/heap-use-after-scope in napi_create_bigint_words() for negatives.

For a negative bigint (signBit set) it built the 2's-complement words into a
SmallVector declared inside the `if` block, set `words = negativeValue.data()`,
then read `words` via BigIntPrimitive::fromBytes() AFTER the block closed and the
SmallVector was destroyed. initWithBytes() memcpy's from that freed storage
(SmallVector's inline buffer is on the stack -> stack-use-after-scope; spilled to
heap for wordCount > 16 -> heap-use-after-free). It happened to work in
non-ASan builds because the stack window was not yet clobbered, but it is UB and
AddressSanitizer flags it (BigIntSupport.cpp:138, via js-native-api test_bigint
TestWords). Hoist negativeValue to function scope so it outlives fromBytes().
diff --git a/API/hermes_node_api/hermes_node_api.cpp b/API/hermes_node_api/hermes_node_api.cpp
--- a/API/hermes_node_api/hermes_node_api.cpp
+++ b/API/hermes_node_api/hermes_node_api.cpp
@@ -5518,9 +5518,16 @@
 
   vm::GCScope gcScope{env->runtime_};
 
+  // Holds the 2's-complement words for a negative bigint. It must outlive the
+  // fromBytes() call below (which reads `words`), so it lives at function scope.
+  // Previously it was declared inside the `if`, leaving `words` dangling into
+  // freed storage after the block — a stack/heap-use-after-scope read in
+  // initWithBytes() (caught by ASan; worked by luck without it).
+  llvh::SmallVector<uint64_t, 16> negativeValue;
+
   if (signBit) {
     // Use 2's complement algorithm to represent negative numbers.
-    llvh::SmallVector<uint64_t, 16> negativeValue{words, words + wordCount};
+    negativeValue.assign(words, words + wordCount);
 
     // a. flip all bits
     for (uint64_t &entry : negativeValue) {
